{
  "query": "What actions can be taken to mitigate the environmental pollution caused by waste from salmon farms?",
  "answer": "To mitigate pollution from salmon farm waste, key actions include integrating aquaculture systems, cleaning wastewater before discharge, and establishing fallowing periods.\n\nIntegrated aquaculture systems, such as multi-trophic approaches like combining salmon with mussels and seaweed (Action ID 932), can naturally reduce pollution by recycling waste nutrients through species interactions, fostering water purification and nutrient reuse. Cleaning wastewater through primary, secondary, and tertiary treatments (Action ID 1778)\u2014including methods like filtration or wetland-based nutrient stripping\u2014removes harmful pollutants like heavy metals or excess nutrients before environmental release, limiting contamination of water bodies. Establishing fallowing periods (Action ID 1027) involves periodically ceasing fish farming operations at sites for weeks to months, enabling natural dilution of accumulated waste such as organic matter and sediments, which supports sediment recovery and maintains biodiversity. Combining these strategies addresses direct waste by-products while reinforcing ecological balance in aquaculture zones. By tailoring treatments to specific pollutants and monitoring recovery during rest phases, pollution impacts from salmon farms can be substantially reduced.",
  "action_ids": [
    "932",
    "1778",
    "1027"
  ]
}

