{
  "query": "What are the most effective ways to increase soil organic carbon on loamy soils?",
  "answer": "The most effective ways to increase soil organic carbon on loamy soils include reducing tillage, incorporating legumes into crop rotations, growing cover crops, and amending with chemical fertilizers.\n\nReducing or eliminating tillage consistently increases soil organic carbon, as twelve studies globally demonstrated elevated carbon levels under no-tillage systems in loam and silt-loam soils due to minimized soil disturbance and reduced oxidation of organic matter [906]. Incorporating legumes like forage crops into rotations specifically boosts soil organic carbon, as evidenced by controlled trials in Canada and Denmark that measured increased carbon storage when cycling legumes through farmland rotations on loam soils [857]. Planting cover crops such as ryegrass during fallow periods further enhances carbon sequestration, with studies in Denmark showing higher carbon accumulation in loam soils and UK trials noting improved soil structure and reduced nutrient leaching when establishing off-season vegetation ground cover [898]. Amending loamy soils with nitrogen or phosphorus fertilizers also supports organic carbon retention, as six different studies across multiple countries revealed increased organic matter and nutrient efficiency in loam, sandy loam, and silt-loam soils when these formulations were applied [909]. Collectively, these approaches minimize soil disruption, leverage biological nitrogen fixation, maintain continuous root systems, and optimize nutrient management to enhance carbon storage specifically in loamy soil textures.",
